{"key":"post-6610766","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>6610766</id>\n<content>You can see that perlite is crystalline and impervious to water, but with a large surface area to hold and evaporate it off from. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Vermiculite is soft and resembles a mineral sponge, able to soak up water and hold it.&amp;nbsp; Vermiculite also has lots of passageways the mycelium can colonize while absorbing the moisture within.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Hopefully, these pictures will put to rest the idea of substituting one for the other.&amp;nbsp; They're not even remotely similar.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577963-Perlite_1a.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577963-thumb_Perlite_1a.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577974-Vermiculite_0a.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577974-thumb_Vermiculite_0a.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577983-Perlite-vermiculite-dime_1a.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/07-008/246577983-thumb_Perlite-vermiculite-dime_1a.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-008/246577993-Perlite-vermiculite-dime_2.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;he